{
  "text": "Additional support for that idea came from the report of increased g binding after amygdala kindling [CITATION_1] and C-diprenorphine-induced seizures [CITATION_2] . Enhanced binding occurred primarily in portions of the cortex, amygdala, caudate putamen, central gray, thalamus, and substantia nigra [CITATION_3] . Nearly a month later, however, lower than normal binding occurred in some areas [CITATION_4] . After seizures induced by C-diprenorphine, binding in the cortex increased, but because overall binding remained the same, non-u binding, primarily K, decreased. This might help explain the findings of anticonvulsant properties of K agonists [CITATION_5] .",
